<div class="ref-intro">
  <h1>Plugin System</h1>
  <p>The plugin system splits storage, webhook delivery, and auth into independently swappable <strong>capability namespaces</strong>. You can run markdown-backed cards with S3 attachments, or SQLite cards with a custom auth policy — without touching application code.</p>
  <div class="capability-grid">
    <div class="capability-card">
      <strong>card.storage</strong>
      <span>Where cards and comments are persisted. Built-ins: <code>markdown</code>, <code>sqlite</code>. External: <code>kl-mysql-storage</code>.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="capability-card">
      <strong>attachment.storage</strong>
      <span>Where file attachments are stored. Built-in: local filesystem. External: <code>kl-s3-attachment-storage</code>.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="capability-card">
      <strong>webhook.delivery</strong>
      <span>Outbound HTTP delivery for kanban events. External: <code>kl-webhooks-plugin</code>.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="capability-card">
      <strong>auth.identity / auth.policy</strong>
      <span>Identity resolution and action-level authorization. Built-in: no-op. Package: <code>kl-auth-plugin</code>.</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="usage-example">
    <strong>Select providers in <code>.kanban.json</code></strong>
    <pre><code>{
  "storage": {
    "card.storage":        { "provider": "sqlite" },
    "attachment.storage": { "provider": "kl-s3-attachment-storage" },
    "webhook.delivery":   { "provider": "webhooks" }
  }
}</code></pre>
  </div>
</div>

